Case Study: Phishing Attack
Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers impersonate trusted organizations or individuals to trick victims into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, bank details, or credit card numbers. It typically happens through fraudulent emails, text messages, or fake websites designed to look legitimate.
Step-by-step process:
- The attacker creates a convincing email or message that appears to come from a trusted source (e.g., a bank or university).
- The message usually contains urgent language, such as “Your account will be blocked unless you verify now.”
- A link is provided that directs the victim to a fake website resembling the real one.
- The victim enters their login credentials or financial details.
- The attacker collects this information and uses it for unauthorized access or financial theft.
Targets: Phishing attacks often target everyday internet users, especially those less familiar with digital security practices. Students, employees, and online shoppers are common victims.
Consequences: Victims may face financial loss, identity theft, or unauthorized transactions. Organizations can suffer reputational damage and data breaches if employees fall prey to phishing.
Real Incident: In 2020, Google reported blocking over 18 million phishing emails related to COVID-19 scams each day, showing how widespread and dangerous this crime can be 
Phishing remains one of the most prevalent cybercrimes, highlighting the importance of digital literacy and awareness in protecting personal and organizational data.



 Part B – Prevention Checklist & Reflection:

Stay Safe Online Checklist (for College Students in India)
✅ Prevention Tips
- Use strong, unique passwords for all accounts and enable two-factor authentication.
- Always verify links and sender addresses before clicking on emails or messages.
- Keep your devices updated with the latest security patches and antivirus software.
- Log out of shared or public computers after use.
- Be cautious when sharing personal details on social media—limit visibility with privacy settings.
- For UPI/Online Payments: Never share your UPI PIN or OTP with anyone.
- For UPI/Online Payments: Double-check merchant names and transaction amounts before approving payments.
- Report suspicious activity immediately through the National Cyber Crime Portal (cybercrime.gov.in) or the Helpline 1930.
While researching cybercrime prevention, what surprised me most was the sheer scale of phishing and UPI fraud cases reported daily in India. I realized that even small lapses, like clicking on an unverified link or casually sharing personal details, can lead to serious financial and identity theft issues. The fact that fraudsters often exploit urgency and fear in their messages made me more aware of how psychological manipulation plays a big role in cybercrime.
One habit I will personally change is being more cautious with online payments. I often approve UPI transactions quickly without double-checking details, but now I will carefully verify every transaction before entering my PIN. This small step can significantly reduce the risk of falling victim to online payment fraud.
